{"Body": "<p>\n</p><p>There was no rise in the student service charge in the budget this year. In last month&rsquo;s budget the Minister for Finance left the student service charge (registration fee) unchanged at &euro;1,500.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Irish Independent reported that a confidential government document which it had seen showed the government recently considered hiking the charge by as much as &euro;1,000. An increase by this much would raise an extra &euro;54m.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The 2009 budget allowed the registration fee to be increased from &euro;900 to &euro;1,500 in colleges for the 2009/2010 academic year.</p>\n<p>The government sets a maximum registration fee and after consulting the Higher Education Authority (HEA) each college sets its own fee. &nbsp;</p>\n<p>The student service charge has been had some attention in the last couple of months the Joint Education and Science committee heard that only a third of Trinity&rsquo;s student service charge for 2008/09 academic year was spent on student services. The accounts produced by Trinity College were sent to the chairman of the education committee and Green party TD Paul Gogarty.</p>\n<p>The student service charge is supposed to be ring fenced for student services, exams, and registration.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>In a letter to Gogarty explaining Trinity SU&rsquo;s argument on the student service charge C&oacute;n&aacute;n &Oacute; Broin, Students&rsquo; Union President, says that the Minister for Education is on record saying that the student service charge is &lsquo;solely for the provision of student services.&rsquo;</p>\n<p>The student service charge was introduced in 1996 when the Government started to pay tuition fees. A charge of &pound;150 was paid by students for services, registration, and examinations.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Department for Education circular on the student service charge says that examination and registration fees have always been regarded as a separate issue. &lsquo;Second level students pay an examination fee for sitting the Junior and Leaving Certificate examination,&rsquo; the circular says.</p>\n<p>The estimates for 2009 say that the College collected &euro;8,283,371 from student service charge. The estimates also indicate that the College budgeted &euro;1,351,000 for examinations and &euro;1,435,425 on the costs of registration for 2009.</p>\n<p>The budget also made changes for those start college next year and who qualify for the back-to-education allowance. Those who are entitled to receive the allowance will no longer be eligible for a grant.</p>\n<p>Previously, those who received a back-to-education allowance were also allowed claim a grant and apply for the top-up grant.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Trinity College Students&rsquo; Union&rsquo;s Mature Student Officer, Simone Cameron-Coen said the government &lsquo;wants to encourage people off social welfare and back to education and training, by pulling much needed funding from the poorest part of society they are actively discouraging a return to education.&rsquo;</p>\n<p>The amount of the grants and scholarships were reduced by five per cent. It will apply to all incoming and current students from January 2010. These measures will achieve a &euro;10m saving for the state.</p>\n", "Imageurl": "<p>\n</p><p>There was no rise in the student service charge in the budget this year. In last month&rsquo;s budget the Minister for Finance left the student service charge (registration fee) unchanged at &euro;1,500.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Irish Independent reported that a confidential government document which it had seen showed the government recently considered hiking the charge by as much as &euro;1,000. An increase by this much would raise an extra &euro;54m.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The 2009 budget allowed the registration fee to be increased from &euro;900 to &euro;1,500 in colleges for the 2009/2010 academic year.</p>\n<p>The government sets a maximum registration fee and after consulting the Higher Education Authority (HEA) each college sets its own fee. &nbsp;</p>\n<p>The student service charge has been had some attention in the last couple of months the Joint Education and Science committee heard that only a third of Trinity&rsquo;s student service charge for 2008/09 academic year was spent on student services. The accounts produced by Trinity College were sent to the chairman of the education committee and Green party TD Paul Gogarty.</p>\n<p>The student service charge is supposed to be ring fenced for student services, exams, and registration.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>In a letter to Gogarty explaining Trinity SU&rsquo;s argument on the student service charge C&oacute;n&aacute;n &Oacute; Broin, Students&rsquo; Union President, says that the Minister for Education is on record saying that the student service charge is &lsquo;solely for the provision of student services.&rsquo;</p>\n<p>The student service charge was introduced in 1996 when the Government started to pay tuition fees. A charge of &pound;150 was paid by students for services, registration, and examinations.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>The Department for Education circular on the student service charge says that examination and registration fees have always been regarded as a separate issue. &lsquo;Second level students pay an examination fee for sitting the Junior and Leaving Certificate examination,&rsquo; the circular says.</p>\n<p>The estimates for 2009 say that the College collected &euro;8,283,371 from student service charge. The estimates also indicate that the College budgeted &euro;1,351,000 for examinations and &euro;1,435,425 on the costs of registration for 2009.</p>\n<p>The budget also made changes for those start college next year and who qualify for the back-to-education allowance. Those who are entitled to receive the allowance will no longer be eligible for a grant.</p>\n<p>Previously, those who received a back-to-education allowance were also allowed claim a grant and apply for the top-up grant.&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Trinity College Students&rsquo; Union&rsquo;s Mature Student Officer, Simone Cameron-Coen said the government &lsquo;wants to encourage people off social welfare and back to education and training, by pulling much needed funding from the poorest part of society they are actively discouraging a return to education.&rsquo;</p>\n<p>The amount of the grants and scholarships were reduced by five per cent. It will apply to all incoming and current students from January 2010. These measures will achieve a &euro;10m saving for the state.</p>\n", "Thumb_nail": "http://universitytimes.ie/wp-content/uploads/2013/utlogo.jpg", "ID": "560", "Heading": "Budget 2010 sees education cuts, but no rise in student service change"}